data.body:
- VSCode Version: 1.0.0
- OS Version: Windows 10

Steps to Reproduce:
1. Add following code to main.ts

   ``` typescript
   import { window, commands, OutputChannel, Disposable, ExtensionContext} from 'vscode';

   let channel: OutputChannel;

   export function activate(context: ExtensionContext): void {
   registerCommands(context);
   channel = window.createOutputChannel('Compile');
   context.subscriptions.push(channel);
   }

   export function deactivate(context: ExtensionContext): void {
   console.log('deactivated');
   }

   function registerCommands(context: ExtensionContext): void {
   let c1: Disposable = commands.registerCommand('test1', () => {
       var test: number = 0;
       (function testFunc() {
           channel.appendLine(`test: ${test++}`);
           setTimeout(function(){
               testFunc();
           },2000);
       })();
   });
   context.subscriptions.push(c1);
   }
   ```
2. Add this to package.json (remember to change main value to compiled js)

   ``` json
   {
   "main": "<path-to-js>",
   "activationEvents": [
       "onCommand:gcc-compile"
   ],
   "contributes": {
       "commands": [
           {
               "command": "test1",
               "title": "MY TEST 1"
           }
       ]
   }
   }
   ```
3. When you run the command multiple times, the previous instances don't shutdown. This will create an issue especially if a continuous command (such as watcher) is running. The only way to stop commands is to close Visual Studio Code.

Suggesions:
1. Function to stop one of the currently running commands.
2. Force single instance of an extension command.
3. A function similar to `export function deactivate(context: ExtensionContext)` that runs before every command call. One of the parameters should be an array of currently running commands with the ability to deactivate them.
